export const batch167 = {
  "talking-to-strangers.json": {
    base: { id: "talking-to-strangers", title: "Talking to Strangers", author: "", type: "summary", addedAt: 1781606071657 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: "Can we ever truly know another person?",
        text: "Quick check-in before we begin. This is a placeholder section because the original page did not load. Your connection looks fine and the host is fine. The original platform returned a 500 error when trying to render the opening reflection. Treat this as a clean slate. The next section picks up the actual story."
      },
      {
        title: "The trap of seeing what we expect",
        text: "Storm clouds gathered across Europe in the late 1930s, when Adolf Hitler pressed his claim on the Sudetenland, a slice of what was then Czechoslovakia. The German leader cast a long shadow over the whole continent. Even so, British Prime Minister Neville Chamberlain and Foreign Secretary Lord Halifax traveled to meet him in person. Both came back charmed by Hitler and his polished manners. They believed his promise not to touch Czechoslovakia. Less than six months later, he broke that promise and triggered the second world war.\n\nBefore we write them off as naive leaders, pause and think about your own life. Maybe you trusted a smooth salesperson who turned out to be hiding the catch. Maybe a romantic partner showered you with affection before showing a darker side. Maybe a coworker seemed supportive in meetings only to throw you under the bus later. The pattern feels familiar, and the seasoned politicians fell into the same trap you can fall into today.\n\nA few years back, the American psychologist Emily Pronin ran a study that showed people believe they understand others better than others understand them. The participants filled in word fragments that could become \"touch\" or \"tough\" and \"treat\" or \"defeat,\" among other pairs. They assumed their own word choices revealed nothing personal about them. Yet they eagerly formed opinions about each other based on those very choices. Nobody caught the contradiction. They had slipped into what she called the illusion of asymmetric insight.\n\nWhen we think we know someone better than they know themselves, we stop paying attention. We lose the habit of listening and fall back on assumptions. A person tends to open up only when you offer a real ear to listen. Chamberlain never doubted his plan to prevent war. Yet he paid a steep price for his inattention, and his talks with Hitler stand among the most pointless in history. The same pattern shows up in everyday life. In job interviews we read a candidate in five minutes. On dating apps we swipe in a split second. In parent-teacher conferences we draw big conclusions from one short talk.\n\nListening rarely gets credit as a basic skill in conversation, but you can change that today. The next time you want to know someone, ask yourself what you stand to gain by picturing them as something they are not. Remember, everyone eventually shows who they really are, and you do not need to do that work for them.\n\nWe jump at the chance to judge strangers. We would never treat ourselves that way, of course. That line belongs to Malcolm Gladwell."
      },
      {
        title: "Trust has to come before trust worthiness",
        text: "Ana Montes earned a strong reputation as one of the most trusted analysts at the Defense Intelligence Agency. At the time Cuba, under Fidel Castro, sat high on the agency watch list, so when several small coincidences stacked up within a few days, alarm bells started ringing. What caught the eye of counterintelligence analyst Reg Brown was a loose thread connecting Ana Montes to research she had done in Cuba.\n\nShe did not slip up under questioning. Her alibi held together. The case was set aside until five years later, when the agency learned that Montes had been passing classified material to Cuba. Every night after work, she put her sharp memory to use and sent key details to the Cuban government. She had been working for them from the day she joined.\n\nSo how did she fool an entire agency of trained professionals. The answer may sit inside the Truth-Default Theory, or TDT.\n\nA worn cover can still give up fresh secrets if you know what to look for. Here is the idea. TDT says our first guess about another person is that they are being honest with us. A study led by Timothy R. Levine, a communication studies professor at the University of Alabama at Birmingham, found that people are better at spotting a truth teller than a liar. He called this habit the default to truth, which gave the theory its name. Montes's colleagues made a serious but very human mistake. They assumed she was telling the truth and overlooked the warning signs. Her outspoken criticism of American policy in Central America gave Cuban handlers a way to recruit her.\n\nHere is a small action you can try this week. When someone tells you something that feels important or surprising, give it twenty four hours before you fully accept it. Use that time to look for evidence that supports or contradicts their story.\n\nMontes was prosecuted and sentenced to twenty five years in prison for spying for Cuba. She was released on January 6, 2023, and she remains under supervision today.\n\nWhat is the lesson. A baseline level of trust in new people is natural and healthy, yet her case shows that inner debriefs and clear thinking matter when a situation calls for them."
      },
      {
        title: "Strangers act strangely when they meet us",
        text: "In 2007, the exchange student Meredith Kercher was murdered by Rudy Guede in Perugia, Italy. The evidence pointed to Guede, yet the spotlight fell on her roommate Amanda Knox. Her reaction to the murder looked wrong to many viewers, and she lost four years of her freedom before being cleared. What sent the investigation in the wrong direction.\n\nKnox's story could happen to any of us. Picture a partner who reacts to bad news in a way you would not expect. How fast do you judge their character based on that reaction. Amanda was calm and did not appear to grieve her roommate in public. Her behavior tells us about two ideas, the mismatch and the illusion of transparency.\n\nGoing back to Tim Levine's study, each participant was paired with an instructor and a lab partner they did not know. The partner had been instructed to lure the participant into cheating when the instructor left the room, and Levine later checked who lied. One woman defied the pattern. She told the truth even though her body language was jumpy and nervous. The takeaway is clear. You cannot always read truth or lies on a face.\n\nIn her later memoir, Knox described herself as a strange kid who played a dangerous game and acted in ways people read as suspicious in that setting. Her surface behavior did not match the truth, but she was not the only one whose reactions misled others. Ana Montes's calm response when accused should have raised alarms at the agency. She looked unbothered on the outside while panicking within.\n\nConfidence does not always point to a truth teller, and nervousness does not always expose a liar. A separate study by German psychologists Achim Schützwohl and Rainer Reisenzein showed that facial expressions can be milder than the feelings behind them. Some participants, for example, did not open their eyes wide or scream when startled. They looked outwardly calm.\n\nClear communication is hard because behavior and words do not always line up, which creates the illusion of transparency. We cannot rely on words alone without seeing the person, because the truth hides in the gap between the two. Think about your own reactions. Do you always react the way you think you should. Do you laugh when you feel nervous, go quiet when you feel overwhelmed, or act confident when you are scared. If other people judged you on those surface reactions alone, would they see who you really are."
      },
      {
        title: "The stranger inside someone never goes away",
        text: "In March 2003, the CIA captured one of the most dangerous Al-Qaeda figures, Khalid Sheikh Mohammed, known as KSM. His interrogation made its mark on agency history. KSM admitted to the murder of Wall Street Journal reporter Daniel Pearl. He said he had greeted Pearl by name as if they were friends, then executed him. The confession haunted the professional psychologist and interrogator James Mitchell. He and his colleague Bruce Jensen worked on enhanced interrogation techniques, or EITs, under the SERE program, which stands for Survival, Evasion, Resistance, and Escape.\n\nSleep deprivation, slamming into walls, and waterboarding were seen as the most effective tools. Even their combined effect had to build up over time before KSM's will gave way. In the end, he confessed to involvement in multiple operations in the name of Jihad.\n\nOn the surface this looked like a win for American intelligence, but the psychiatrist Charles Morgan saw it differently. His research on post-traumatic stress disorder cast doubt on the value of those enhanced techniques. The question he asked before the research was simple. Why do some veterans suffer from PTSD while others walk away from highly stressful events largely intact. To find the answer, he studied soldiers at the SERE school and was surprised by what he saw.\n\nAt the school, disciplined and organized soldiers reacted to the replica prisoner of war camp as if it were real. Their prefrontal cortex, the part of the brain that supports rational thought, dropped to a prepubescent level. That is what happened to the man behind the 9/11 attacks. KSM was so sleep deprived that he would have confessed to anything, even acts he did not commit. So another question waits for us. Did the interrogation actually achieve anything.\n\nThe same principle shows up in daily relationships. When someone feels cornered, criticized, or exhausted, their rational thinking shuts down. A parent who feels overwhelmed may agree to unreasonable demands. A stressed employee may confess to mistakes they did not make just to end the pressure.\n\nOne thing is certain. We may not know everything about the person in front of us, even when they are not a stranger. The second sure thing is that we can damage a relationship by pushing someone past their limits. You cannot force openness by shoving someone out of their comfort zone.\n\nAccording to Mitchell's SERE research, women showed a more steady and clear headed response to threats against their colleagues than men did."
      },
      {
        title: "Inside the minds of people in despair",
        text: "A note before we begin. This chapter mentions suicide.\n\nMany of us have known someone who seemed to struggle in silence. Maybe they looked fine on the surface but were fighting battles we could not see. The hard truth is that we often miss the warning signs because we assume we know what despair looks like. People's responses to crisis are far more layered than we imagine.\n\nSylvia Plath was thirty when she took her own life after a long battle with clinical depression. Her death by carbon monoxide poisoning was a deliberate choice, not a rash act. She had made earlier attempts, but the final one was planned so carefully that her intent could not be doubted. Why did Sylvia Plath make the choice she did, and what can her death teach us about strangers.\n\nMalcolm Gladwell offers two ideas. The first is displacement. It assumes that a person set on self harm will find another way if the first option is removed. The second is coupling. It combines specific conditions and behaviors so that a risky act only happens when those pieces line up. These two ideas pull in opposite directions. Most people lean toward displacement and assume that a suicidal person will simply pick another method. Under that view, monitoring well known suicide spots would not help.\n\nOn the other hand, research by the psychologist Richard Seiden found that certain behaviors are tightly bound to a specific setting. The Golden Gate Bridge, for example, is well known among people with suicidal thoughts. The coupling view suggests that adding a safety net to the bridge could deter attempts there. In their minds, the choice to act was tied to that very place, so they would not repeat the attempt elsewhere or in another form.\n\nSylvia Plath's death is a painful example. She tried to take her own life in several different ways before she found the one she was least afraid of. Accept that hope rises and falls. It is normal for it to ebb and flow.\n\nWhat does her story teach us about strangers. First, we remain attached to the default to truth and the illusion of transparency. Second, we rarely consider whether a new person's behavior can be tied to a specific environment or place. We think in displacement terms, as if people's ways of acting do not shift. When we notice coupling, it becomes easier to see the new person as complex and layered, and that helps us respond with more compassion."
      },
      {
        title: "Closing thoughts",
        text: "All people, whether we just met them or have known them for years, hold secrets. It is human nature to keep a little space for things that belong only to us, and we should remember that every time our brain wants to slap a label on someone.\n\nWe have seen that humans can be naive at their own cost, but society would grow paranoid if we doubted every single thing and every single person. A little inexperience is not the worst thing, so we should not beat ourselves up when someone turns out to be different from what we expected. Our hearts are built to trust, but trust needs practice to grow.\n\nTry this. Here is your five day Stranger Challenge, one small action per day that can shift how you connect.\n\nDay one. During a hard conversation, catch yourself pushing for answers or explanations. Pause and say, \"I am here when you are ready to talk.\" Wait. Notice how the other person responds.\n\nDay two. The moment someone's reaction confuses you, stop and write down three different reasons they might be responding that way before deciding what it means.\n\nDay three. When someone acts out of character, perhaps the usually cheerful coworker looks withdrawn, or the quiet friend speaks up boldly, ask yourself what just happened before this. What setting are they in. What pressure might they be feeling.\n\nDay four. Track your own behavior changes. Are you more confident at your favorite coffee shop. More irritable in crowded places. More creative at certain times of day. Write down how context shapes your reactions.\n\nDay five. Pick one important conversation and commit to asking two questions for every one thing you share about yourself. Use phrases like \"Tell me more about that\" and \"How did that feel for you.\"\n\nThe goal is to grow more curious about the depth in every person you meet. In the end, we are all strangers moving through the world together, trying to be understood while learning to truly see others."
      }
    ]
  },

  "thanksgiving-the-holiday-at-the-heart-of-the-american-experience.json": {
    base: { id: "thanksgiving-the-holiday-at-the-heart-of-the-american-experience", title: "Thanksgiving", author: "", type: "summary", addedAt: 1781684330825 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: "A holiday that belongs to everyone",
        text: "When Melanie Kirkpatrick visited Newcomers High School in Queens, a public school that serves mostly children from immigrant families, she planned to share the history of Thanksgiving and listen to how the students marked the holiday at home.\n\nShe quickly saw that the holiday's values touched the students deeply. They began treating it as an anchor in their new lives in America. Different as their backgrounds were, the holiday carried the same meaning for all of them, a sense of belonging, community support, and hope for the future. They folded traditions from their home countries into American customs. A Polish family, for example, served pierogi next to their turkey.\n\nIn a globalized world, weaving the traditions of several cultures into one celebration adds real meaning.\n\nTurkey, parades, family gatherings, and giving thanks are the familiar beats of the day. Behind each one there are personal stories waiting to be told, both in moments of joy and in moments of loss. Walk with me and their stories will come along."
      },
      {
        title: "How Thanksgiving came to be Thanksgiving",
        text: "How well do you know the Thanksgiving story. The famous 1621 celebration in Plymouth, where two peoples came together, was not actually America's first Thanksgiving. The fuller story turns out to be more interesting.\n\nThe Pilgrims, who were mostly Calvinists, endured a long and brutal journey to the shores of New England and lost many members of their community along the way. Every year brought a fight to set aside enough food for winter, so each day was a chance to give thanks. They prayed and thanked God throughout the day, every morning, between work, before meals, and before bed. What we now call Thanksgiving would have been just another day of thanks for them.\n\nThat 1621 gathering, and the ones that came after, gave the Pilgrims a chance to strengthen ties with local tribes, pick up new knowledge, and try to convert Native Americans to Christianity.\n\nIt is also worth remembering that the timing and shape of these gatherings varied across what would become the United States. The Massachusetts Bay Colony, for example, held its own version of Thanksgiving as early as 1630.\n\nEven the Dutch, who explored the continent and built New Netherland in what is now New York City, started similar gatherings in the 1640s. They used these peaceful events to rebuild ties after conflicts with Native Americans.\n\nBefore it became the unifying holiday we know today, Thanksgiving went through many dark chapters and double standards. The widely loved painting The First Thanksgiving at Plymouth by Jennie Brownscombe, painted in 1914, contains several inaccuracies. The landscape suggests a late autumn setting, although the first gathering happened in late summer, right after the harvest. The painting also shows women eating with Native Americans and Pilgrims, but they were more likely busy preparing the meal. The Native Americans in the painting wear bright feathered headdresses typical of western tribes rather than the traditional dress of New England's Indigenous peoples."
      },
      {
        title: "When the president set the example",
        text: "Skip ahead a few centuries to another pivotal moment. In 1789, George Washington, the founder and first president of the United States, declared a national Thanksgiving celebration. As if he sensed he was about to set an example for the future, he approached the task with wisdom and a sense of inclusion.\n\nShared traditions help a community form one vision when they are building something new, even a country.\n\nHis proclamation called for unity and thanked God for supporting the new nation, asking for blessings on the daily work of its people. Notably, he did not single out any religion or nationality. His words embraced everyone in the country. He also made a generous gesture by donating to a church and encouraging others to do good.\n\nWashington's speech launched what became an annual tradition of Thanksgiving proclamations by US presidents. Only Thomas Jefferson pushed back, arguing that the Constitution barred presidents from promoting religious messages or practices, even when those messages were meant to preserve tradition rather than promote the president's faith.\n\nJefferson also pointed out that there was no penalty for not celebrating Thanksgiving. He worried that formal presidential proclamations could feed public skepticism and weaken the office. Why Jefferson focused so tightly on the details of the proclamations instead of encouraging unity remains a mystery. What is clear today is that his arguments did not persuade every future president. Following Washington's unofficial template, Abraham Lincoln mentioned God in his Thanksgiving speech, Theodore Roosevelt spoke of the greatest Giver, and Franklin Roosevelt thanked the father of all people.\n\nThat line about self-sufficiency and gratitude comes from an old Educational Research Bulletin piece on Thanksgiving Day."
      },
      {
        title: "Thank you, Sarah",
        text: "Thanksgiving becoming a national holiday was shaped not only by heads of state but also by some unexpected figures who left their mark in quieter ways.\n\nOne such person was Sarah Josepha Hale, a name rarely found on lists of famous feminists, powerful editors, or Thanksgiving history. Born in 1788 to parents who believed in educating sons and daughters equally, she picked up a college level education through her brother's guidance.\n\nIgnoring what society expected, she waited until she was twenty five to marry, considered late at the time. She married a lawyer, and the couple spent two hours each evening studying literature, French, and biology together.\n\nAfter ten years of marriage, her husband died and left her alone with four children. That challenge pushed her writing forward. After publishing a powerful novel about slavery, Northwood: A Tale of New England, the text caught the eye of a magazine publisher, Godey's Lady's Book, leading to a forty year role as its editor. During her tenure, the magazine became the most famous periodical in the country before the Civil War.\n\nGodey's Lady's Book became her platform for promoting Thanksgiving, which she cherished, as a national holiday. For Hale, the unifying power of the holiday could help reduce racism and sexism, lift patriotism, and bridge America's political divides.\n\nSincere enthusiasm for someone's work inspires others to find creative paths to their goals.\n\nTo spread the idea, she used articles featuring holiday recipes and short stories about cozy family weekends that many readers enjoyed. As readers pictured themselves in those warm scenes, sharing laughs around a table with a juicy turkey, the holiday's appeal grew.\n\nEven during the Civil War, the magazine kept its focus on Thanksgiving. The number of states embracing the celebration kept rising, undeterred by the national conflict."
      },
      {
        title: "The Pilgrims' teacher",
        text: "What do Native Americans think about Thanksgiving. Their ancestors were the ones who first taught the Pilgrims how to live in the new conditions, only to later be forced to fight for their lands and face genocide.\n\nBefore answering that question, step back in time with me. Some Native Americans engaged with European explorers. One of them was Squanto, also called Tisquantum, of the Patuxet tribe of the Wampanoags. His first contact with Europeans began with kidnapping, a common practice at the time. Sailors back then looked for new trade routes and lands, but they also captured locals to sell into slavery or display as curiosities in European exhibitions.\n\nSquanto spent nearly a decade in England. Historians do not know exactly what he was forced to do there, but he ended up learning English and returned to his tribe with an expedition. Not long after, he was kidnapped again. This time he would have been enslaved in Spain if Franciscan friars had not rescued him, converted him to Christianity, and helped him find his way home. No one was waiting for him. His entire community had died from an unknown disease after contact with Europeans.\n\nThe very next year, he met the Pilgrims who had settled near his village. Knowing the language and carrying valuable knowledge, he became their teacher and mentor, paying back the cruelty he had faced with kindness.\n\nDuring some celebrations, it matters to enjoy being together and remember those who made it possible.\n\nFor generations, Native American perspectives on Thanksgiving went unheard. Today, their descendants generally take one of three approaches to the holiday. Some hold a classic Thanksgiving celebration with turkey and a parade. Some spend a family evening exploring the cultures and traditions of various Indigenous communities. Some treat the day as one of remembrance and mourning for the victims of genocide. Each choice deserves respect given what their ancestors went through."
      },
      {
        title: "Turning attention outward",
        text: "Over time, Thanksgiving grew to honor both togetherness and a sense of duty to those facing hardship.\n\nRemember the Friends episode where Phoebe used every trick she could think of to gather donations for children. Her over the top volunteer spirit and her skill at wishing Merry Christmas in different languages captured something real about American giving culture.\n\nThe joy of helping others and the gratitude people feel in return can be worth more than material rewards.\n\nThe first documented mention of Thanksgiving related charity dates back to 1636, when a Massachusetts church hosted a dinner and invited the public. Over time, similar events became standard for many religious organizations around the country.\n\nSince the 19th century, charitable organizations like The Bowery Mission and The Salvation Army have focused on supporting people in need. These groups helped build and popularize the volunteer movement, pulling together people willing to donate both money and time to help others.\n\nThere is another side to this holiday. While Thanksgiving celebrates gratitude and giving, many see Black Friday as its opposite. The day's focus on extreme consumerism and greed pushes people to chase deals rather than share with others.\n\nIn response to Black Friday, activists created the Giving Tuesday initiative, which has spread around the world and now operates in 154 countries. The movement encourages businesses and organizations to launch meaningful social projects and share their results on social networks. Since its creation in 2012, major companies like Microsoft, PayPal, Tinder, and Bitcoin have joined in.\n\nAll these efforts would surely warm Sarah Josepha Hale's heart. Although Thanksgiving did not become the global holiday she dreamed of, its spirit of giving lives on in projects around the world.\n\nThat line about looking back on the year past is from a letter by Abigail Adams."
      },
      {
        title: "Closing thoughts",
        text: "History is made up of many distinct names and actions. Building a brighter future means remembering our past, asking tough questions, and accepting the truth, no matter how bitter it may be. The same spirit applies to the holidays we choose and the way we celebrate them.\n\nTry this. Do not save gratitude only for Thanksgiving. Looking for reasons to be thankful on a regular basis boosts happiness and motivation. Start small and ask yourself what you are grateful for today. Create a new family tradition and pick a place to volunteer. A few hours of your time can make a difference in someone else's life. Keep exploring the holiday's origins, especially through Native American perspectives. Watch documentaries, visit cultural museums, or research the myths and folklore of different tribes. Plan your Black Friday shopping months ahead to avoid impulse purchases you may regret."
      }
    ]
  },

  "the-1619-project.json": {
    base: { id: "the-1619-project", title: "The 1619 Project", author: "", type: "summary", addedAt: 1781684450648 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: "Two sides of the same coin",
        text: "In the long history of North America, one ship played a role that often slips past us. Most people think of the Mayflower, which brought the British Pilgrims to this land in 1620. A year before that, another ship reached the Virginia colony. It marked the start of an era that was also one of the most tragic.\n\nSo what happened in 1619. In August, a ship called The White Lion came to the shores of America carrying several dozen captive Africans. They were sold to the people of Virginia and were the first of the millions who would be considered enslaved on this land over the next 250 years.\n\nBefore World War II, this forced migration stood as the largest in history.\n\nEnslaved people brought knowledge of growing crops, treating rare diseases, and crafting goods. With their labor, they built the economy and the institutions that propped up the young American nation and its democracy. Yet the authorities kept ignoring the rights of these people, who made up one fifth of the country's population.\n\nWhile white men, and only white men at first, since women had almost no rights then, made choices about their homes, careers, and presidents, Black people were not even treated as owners of their own lives. They stayed powerless and invisible on the map of a country they had built with their own hands.\n\nThe 1619 Project became a meaningful investigation for its author as well. Since childhood, Nikole Hannah-Jones had come across success stories that featured the achievements of white people. She did not know what her own ancestors had done to develop the American economy, politics, and social life. The sources she studied showed her that many generations of Black people had been the foundation of that growth, and they had fought on another front for their own freedom and equality.\n\nThis summary looks at events from the era of slavery and after its abolition, and at their impact on modern American society. There is no sugarcoating. Each section offers clear facts so you can draw your own conclusions.\n\nA 2019 Washington Post poll showed that most Americans know very little about the history of slavery, and that they do not have enough knowledge to share with their own children, who grow up without a strong reason to study the topic."
      },
      {
        title: "Where did the idea of race come from",
        text: "People like to sort their lives into categories to feel in control. Buying a house fits in the category of big expenses, and helping another person fits in the category of good deeds. There is one important caveat though. A sense of control should not come from putting labels on other people. It is wrong to judge the value of a human life by placing someone in a category and comparing them with others. A few centuries ago, that principle was not so obvious.\n\nThe sorting of people by race began in the era of slavery. It had calculated political and economic reasons behind it. When a white man had relations with a black woman, it was hard to set the status of their children. Would they get rights like their father or remain in the position of their mother. The rules that were adopted took the second path. Newborn children inherited the race of their mothers and stayed enslaved, which let the enslavers grow their pool of free labor. Black women, who could not protect themselves, their bodies, or their children, were in the worst position of all.\n\nSeveral centuries later, people still run into the urge to assign everyone to their place.\n\nDr. Walter Ashby Plecker was one of the people behind the Racial Integrity Act of 1924, which banned miscegenation and required racial identity to be verified. Plecker pulled together a group of doctors, government clerks, and even undertakers to enforce the law. How could such a document exist in the twentieth century. These were echoes of the colonial era. At that time, gender and race still played a decisive role in many areas of life. The act was finally struck down in 1967, when the US Supreme Court ruled it unconstitutional.\n\nWe can still feel the influence of such laws today. When we fill out certain forms and see a line asking what race we belong to, it is fair to ask why that information is collected and how it will be used, for statistics or for sorting people into boxes."
      },
      {
        title: "Fear turns violent",
        text: "How can someone want something they have never known. How can people who were not born free reach for freedom in a place it was never meant for them. Their longing shows that freedom has always been a universal value, one that should be open to everyone. Enslavers did not draw that conclusion. They did not think they were violating human rights. They only feared losing control of Black people one day, and they feared that any freedom might let enslaved people take revenge.\n\nIn 1669, a law in the Carolina colony gave every white man unlimited power over the people he held captive. They could be sold to other enslavers, forced to work long hours, and poorly fed. What cut deeper was that they could be punished in any way for the smallest mistake. White people controlled the people they called their property and tried to shield themselves from possible uprisings. Their fear grew so large that in the first decades of the 1700s, they set up patrols to keep order and chase down rumors of rebellion.\n\nThere was a fine of 40 shillings for failing to keep proper control over the activities of Black people.\n\nEven so, enslaved people sometimes managed to push back against the injustice directed at them. Those actions were always met with a violent reaction.\n\nIn 1739 in South Carolina, a few dozen enslaved Africans attacked the plantations, killed enslavers, and invited others to join them. All the rebels were tracked down and publicly executed. The following year, a new act required enslaved people to obey the orders of all enslavers. Black people were also forbidden from leaving their workplaces alone or meeting in groups of more than three.\n\nThey were treated as potential criminals and rule breakers by white people. Enslaved people were punished for what they had not done in order to prevent what they might do. Even that could not kill their desire for freedom.\n\nThat line about liberty or death comes from the writer James Baldwin."
      },
      {
        title: "Citizenship gives freedom a voice",
        text: "People gain more rights and opportunities when the country they live in recognizes them as citizens. That sounds obvious. History shows, though, that people who helped build a new state could be treated as if they did not exist. Black people would have a sense of belonging, justice, and safety if they were accepted as full members of American society.\n\nThe first documented record of citizenship comes from Ancient Greece. There, only free adult men could receive the official status of a city citizen.\n\nUntil the 1820s, the American government could not decide what status enslaved people should hold. Workers in state institutions were haunted by the US Constitution, which said that all people are equal. Black activists kept reminding them of that line and pushed back against segregation and for equal rights with other Americans.\n\nThe most important day in this story is January 1, 1863, when Abraham Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation. On that day, the sun of hope rose for enslaved people. They heard from the president that they were being given freedom. Obtaining citizenship became more real in 1868 when a new amendment to the Constitution declared birthright citizenship. That allowed Black people to become US citizens from birth, to count on legal protection, and to vote.\n\nCongress set up the Freedmen's Bureau to take care of newly emancipated citizens. The bureau found housing, guaranteed food and medical care, and looked for grants to fund schools for Black people.\n\nTo support them, authorities in some states organized groups that kept order in the streets and could protect Black people when needed. Notice the shift. A hundred and fifty years earlier, the police had protected white people from attacks by enslaved groups. Now, newly emancipated citizens could need protection from the aggression of white people.\n\nAt the same time, it is worth knowing that these were the first steps toward equality and the end of racism. In the 1870s, Jim Crow laws began to spread across the South. Their purpose was to strip freed people of their rights and chances to grow. These harsh laws kept appearing for decades, sometimes allowing Black people a small measure of political power and sometimes taking it away."
      },
      {
        title: "Where was God in all of this",
        text: "Yes, you read the title right. It is time to talk about God, and about where God was when Black people were enslaved and their lives were reduced to nothing.\n\nWhen enslaved Africans were first brought to America, only their oral culture and beliefs traveled with them. White people called them pagans and used that label to justify cruelty. Over time, cut off from their roots, Black people lost their traditions. They converted to Christianity and baptized their children.\n\nHow could they become Christians and still be enslaved. Enslavers adopted local laws to smooth over that gap, which let the church keep teaching Christianity while ignoring the enslaved status of its members.\n\nThe spread of the gospels, the rise of Black preachers, and access to a basic education gave people room to think about freedom and mutual aid. When they had a chance to gather in church communities, they used those meetings to speak out about the open hypocrisy of Americans. The absurdity made them angry. People who called themselves Christians had enslaved and stripped of all rights those who believed in the same God.\n\nIn the 19th century, two of the most influential Black rights speakers were the preacher James H. Cone and Martin Luther King, Jr.\n\nPeople created the first political organizations out of their religious communities. The churches of newly emancipated citizens fell under an old and familiar fear of white people, who worried about a seizure of power, unrest, and violence. A law can decree that all people become free and equal in rights from a given day, but it takes a great deal of effort and time for them to agree and sincerely believe in such ideas.\n\nOver the following decades, the church became a place with calls for white people to be forgiven, demands for retribution, and the spread of Black nationalism. Worn down by deep disappointment, newly emancipated people tried to recover feelings of compassion and love through faith."
      },
      {
        title: "From fake science to poor medical care",
        text: "In the history of slavery, many crimes committed by white people against Black people went unpunished. Among them were the studies done by doctors and professors on the bodies of enslaved people. The bodies were used for surgery practice or for trying out new treatments. Under the label of research, doctors put forward \"discoveries\" about Black bodies. These were made up claims that no one checked.\n\nIn 1787, Dr. Benjamin Moseley argued in a treatise, based on subjective assumptions, that Black people can endure pain more easily than white people.\n\nThese \"scientific\" conclusions fed racist theories about deep differences in the bodies of Black and white people. Their harmful effects lingered long after the Civil War. Beyond the struggle for food, newly emancipated people also suffered from poor medical care. Doctors knew that unsanitary conditions and missing vaccinations were unacceptable, but racist stereotypes led them to believe that Black people needed less care, so they treated white patients first.\n\nAccess to treatment began to shift when the Freedmen's Bureau opened its Medical Division to give new citizens access to hospitals and consultations. In 1895, the National Medical Association, or NMA, was founded as the first organization of Black doctors. Their work drew the attention of authorities to health issues, helped fund medical institutions for Black people, and supported campaigns on hygiene. Members of the NMA also pushed for the idea of a public health insurance system open to every citizen.\n\nEven so, the United States still cannot offer equal access to health care for all its people. The covid pandemic made that clear. During the crisis, many Black people in densely populated neighborhoods, who struggled with health insurance, could not count on doctors' services.\n\nIt is fair to admit that status, country of origin, and race still play a serious role in parts of modern American life. The sooner this is acknowledged by the authorities and the public, the sooner real change can begin."
      },
      {
        title: "Music as a shared inheritance",
        text: "The one thing white people envied was the music of Black people. Without those musical traditions, the world would never have heard the blues, jazz, and rock and roll. Before the first captive Africans set foot on American soil in 1619, white people had never heard melodies and songs quite like those.\n\nDuring work on the plantations, during building projects, and at evening gatherings around the fire, enslaved people sang songs they had brought from home. They passed oral stories from one to another, created ballads, and stayed connected while they worked. It was their main way of making their lives sound and heard.\n\nFor a long time, Black people were not allowed to use musical instruments. The music came only from their voices and from the sounds of nature around them.\n\nAs Black people became more familiar with Christianity, they began to weave biblical stories into their songs. These spirituals caught the attention of white listeners, who wanted access to the music. They started writing down the melodies so they could be reproduced. In 1867, the first collection called Slave Songs of the United States was published.\n\nMusic also gave newly emancipated people a way to share space with white people, though those spaces were mostly dance floors or halls. The former worked and played instruments after their main jobs, while the latter rested and had fun.\n\nThis is an important point. Black music was treated as entertainment, plain and simple. Because of that, the careers of Louis Armstrong, Ella Fitzgerald, Nina Simone, and other brilliant performers took a long time to be recognized. The understanding that their lyrics, performance, and instrumental work were unique only came with the broader recognition that emancipated people deserved respect and the right to grow professionally."
      },
      {
        title: "Moments that shift how people think",
        text: "On February 1, 1960, four Black students from North Carolina Agricultural and Technical State University walked up to a lunch counter. They stopped near a Whites Only sign and ordered coffee. Nobody was going to fill their order, but the students stayed by the counter for the entire day.\n\nThe 1619 Project includes a short story about that day, written by the American novelist Terry McMillan. Her piece From Behind the Counter paints a vivid picture of what the counter clerk felt as he watched the four students.\n\nThe clerk, like his visitors, was Black. He panicked when he saw the students move toward the Whites Only sign. He ignored their coffee order and did not look them in the eye at first. He could not understand how such an act was even possible.\n\nOn the other hand, who had put that sign there and why. Who decided that Black and white people could not eat at the same table. The clerk did not have answers to those questions, but he felt sure that something had shifted in his own mind. Once the counter emptied, he poured himself a coffee and sat down by the sign.\n\nThe four students were taken away by the police. They came back the next day, and with them, people in other states began sit-ins at lunch counters across the South.\n\nRemember the names of those four young people. David Richmond, Franklin McCain, Joseph McNeil, and Ezell Blair. They were among the brave souls who stepped up to show others that things could be different. Over the years, the number of such stories has only grown. By the summer of 1960, many dining areas in the southern states had become accessible to everyone, regardless of race."
      },
      {
        title: "Closing thoughts",
        text: "From 1619 to 1863, dark times held North America in their grip. For several hundred years, this land was shaped by segregation, twisted facts, and cruel treatment of a particular group of people. That past cannot be erased from memory or pulled out of history books. Citizens still feel its traces in the daily life of a country that claims to stand for democracy and freedom.\n\nIt does no good to avoid discussions about slavery. People need to recognize that era as a great wound to humanity and to accept their duty to Black people. Their service to the American nation cannot be overstated. Their work, persistence, cultural heritage, and fight against injustice shaped the development of the United States.\n\nOver that long stretch, newly emancipated people understood that they would often stand alone in their efforts to claim their rights. They had to take active steps on their own to make their presence in society visible. Even today, Black people know that expanding their rights and access to services can also bring unfair reactions from others.\n\nThe time has come to show them that they are not alone in their struggle for freedom, equality, and a real place in the life of the nation. We cannot change the past, but the future is open to change. It can be genuinely bright for everyone if each citizen chooses action over silence and refuses to let old mistakes repeat.\n\nThat line about how we think about history is from Nikole Hannah-Jones.\n\nTry this. Share what you have learned with friends or family. Talk about which facts surprised or upset you, and which you already knew. Discuss your feelings and thoughts out loud. Attend events that take place every year during Black History Month. That kind of self education and contact with other activists helps the work continue."
      }
    ]
  },

  "the-4-day-week.json": {
    base: { id: "the-4-day-week", title: "The 4 Day Week", author: "", type: "summary", addedAt: 1781634846596 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: "A new idea that could reshape work",
        text: "Flexible work arrangements, also called flextime, is a concept that has gained ground over the past decade. It covers any work setup outside the usual 40 hour week. Common examples include telecommuting, part time work, remote work, and condensed workweeks. The closest cousin to a four day week is part time work, where workers trade fewer days for lower pay. The four day week is fundamentally different. Workers put in only four days a week but earn 100 percent of their salary, provided they can hit 100 percent of the productivity their role demands.\n\nIt sounds strange, yet giving workers an extra day off each week has made several companies more productive.\n\nAndrew Barnes came up with the idea on a flight after reading an issue of The Economist. The issue reported two pieces of productivity research done in Canada and the United Kingdom. The studies showed that office workers were productive for only about 1.5 to 2.5 hours out of the eight they were expected to work. Andrew formed a hypothesis that giving workers a free day each week would boost engagement, which would in turn raise productivity and profit. It was just a hypothesis, and he needed a way to test it.\n\nHis company, Perpetual Guardian, became the test subject for the new idea. He looked for business leaders who had tried anything similar in the past but could not find any. He knew there was a lot of work ahead.\n\nAndrew wanted to test the hypothesis in real conditions. He got sign off from the management team and then shared the idea with his employees. Two outside researchers were brought in to make the trial more solid.\n\nThey ran the trial for two months. The results were striking. Perpetual Guardian has now made the four day week a permanent part of its policy.\n\nNews outlets in New Zealand picked up on the success of the experiment and interviewed Andrew about his idea. In social media terms, the concept went viral. Today it is being discussed in 75 countries, and several governments are weighing whether to make it law. Whether you are new to the four day week or already familiar with it, this summary will walk you through the advantages for businesses and society, how to introduce it in your own organization, and the basic pitfalls to avoid so that it works for you."
      },
      {
        title: "Work stress is costing everyone",
        text: "If we freeze frame the world of work as it stands today, we see a few clear patterns. Workers are more distracted than ever. Mental health problems tied to work stress are on the rise. People put in long hours without producing results that match the time spent, and companies lose money because of it.\n\nIn a 2017 survey of nearly 2,000 full time office workers, 79 percent of employees said they were not fully engaged during their 37 to 40 hour work week. In fact, 54 percent admitted that they looked forward to office distractions like chatting with coworkers, making personal phone calls, and browsing news sites during the day.\n\nWhen work feels like the main source of stress, people pull back from it.\n\nIf you are an employer, you may wonder why workers behave this way. Many studies could answer that question, but a recurring theme is that workers give in to small office distractions because work hours are often the only time they have to socialize.\n\nBoth developed and developing countries face long commute problems. Urban housing is expensive in most big cities, so people settle for homes on the outskirts. The result is long commutes in and out of work. Far too many workers have to wake up early to reach work on time and return home late because of traffic. When work life looks like that, it is easy to give in to office distractions because that is the only way to relax and connect with others. Office chatter also helps mental health, which is why workers engage in it regularly.\n\nHas anything been done about long commutes and long hours. Organized labor in some countries has pushed for shorter hours. In Germany, the metalworkers union IG Metall has secured 28 hour work weeks for 900,000 of its members. France is another example, famous for its 35 hour work week.\n\nStill, these short work week policies are not widespread. Most workers around the world are still expected to spend eight hours in the office every day, and many of them must deal with long commutes on top of that.\n\nA 2020 study of American workers, posted by Healthcareers.co, found that workers with higher incomes are more likely to experience stress on the job."
      },
      {
        title: "The four day week is not the gig economy",
        text: "When some business leaders try to push back on the four day week, they say it already exists and point to the gig economy. The two are not the same, so it is worth laying out the differences before going further.\n\nThe gig economy has roots in the United States. Before the late 2000s, the word gig referred to the contracts that musicians and artists booked. A jazz musician was said to have \"gotten a gig\" when they were booked to play a club, for example. Today, a gig can mean anything from freelancing on sites like Fiverr and Upwork to driving for Uber or renting out your home on Airbnb.\n\nThe term gig economy was coined in 2009 by Tina Brown, a former editor of The New Yorker.\n\nLike the four day week, the gig economy promises flexibility and income, which is probably why people mix them up. The big difference is that gig workers lose every protection that comes with traditional work, while the four day week keeps all of those protections and adds more.\n\nA gig worker is paid as long as they keep working. Once they stop or retire, there is no pension to fall back on. They are also on their own when it comes to health care and paid leave, which traditional workers enjoy. To make things harder, gig workers rarely get support to learn new skills. Freelancing on Upwork means you are on your own. The same goes for working for gig platforms like Lyft and Airbnb. Nobody is invested in making you a better professional. If that happens, it is up to you.\n\nThe four day week is not like that. It is traditional work with fewer hours, which means employers must follow standard employment laws covering 401K plans, vacations, and paid leave. Employers also contribute to local, regional, and national economies, unlike gig platforms, which often route work abroad to dodge taxes."
      },
      {
        title: "How to get your organization started",
        text: "This chapter walks through the important steps to run a successful trial and possibly roll out a four day week policy in your organization.\n\nThe first step is to present the idea to management. It can be hard to get buy in because this is still a fairly new policy. A solid way to convince leadership is with hard facts. Look at teams and employees inside the organization before you walk into a board meeting. Find out what your productivity data looks like. For example, you could run independent research and anonymous surveys asking employees how many hours they think they spend on real work each day. Compare your numbers with the UK and Canada research that suggested office workers average 1.5 to 2.5 hours of focused work per day. You will probably find that your workers are more productive than that, but can you show leadership that there is room to improve. Show them what improved productivity means for workers and for the organization, then ask for a trial.\n\nOnce you have sign off from the leaders, it is time to talk to a lawyer. You want to make sure the trial or the full rollout fits within the employment laws of your country or state.\n\nThe third step is engaging employees. This policy does not work without their direct involvement. CEOs like to think of themselves as sharp decision makers, and they are, that is how they climbed the ladder, but without the direct participation of employees, the four day week will not fly.\n\nEmployees need to understand that the free days off are a vote of confidence that they will deliver 100 percent of the expected results in only 80 percent of the time. Bring them into the process before the policy goes live. Make it clear that the 32 hour week is not a fixed arrangement. They do not have to work four days and take a day off. They could choose to shorten hours across five days instead.\n\nAnother step is to tell employees that they are free to flag time wasting factors in their workflow that could be hurting productivity.\n\nFinally, if you start with a trial, analyze the results, ideally with help from an outside researcher, to see what kind of productivity gains or setbacks came from the new policy."
      },
      {
        title: "The four day week is for the greater good",
        text: "Let us zoom out and look at what a four day week can do for society as a whole.\n\nImagine a couple who both work for organizations with flexible hours. They could choose to have a baby without either having to pause their career. That single change would ease both inequality and low fertility rates at once. Spread that picture across cities around the world, and the scale of the benefits comes into view.\n\nFlexible work also helps the environment. With fewer people in the office five days a week, there are fewer cars on the road, which means less traffic congestion and fewer carbon emissions. A New Zealand study found that productivity in the country could rise by about 9.4 million dollars each year if the road network were decongested.\n\nOn community impact, companies can ask workers to spend some of their free days on volunteer work. Perpetual Guardian did this with its employees. Part of its flexible work policy asks workers to spend one of their free days each quarter helping society in some way. With 240 employees, that adds up to nearly 1,000 days of community contribution each year. Imagine what would happen if larger companies asked their workers to do the same.\n\nThe four day week naturally nudges employees to give back to both their employers and the wider community for the free time they receive.\n\nFinally, the four day week makes the world healthier. Having an extra day to relax or do what you love outside work cuts down on work related stress. According to FlexJobs, 80 percent of remote workers say they almost never feel work stress. If the four day week were more widely adopted, the number of de stressed workers could grow even more."
      },
      {
        title: "Do not miss the chance to improve lives",
        text: "Many business leaders lost millions in potential profit because they looked the wrong way while the internet was taking off. Only the visionary leaders who could see what the internet was becoming took advantage of it, and they are light years ahead of their colleagues today.\n\nWith every innovation, there are always late adopters, the group of skeptics who refuse to believe something can work until everyone else has already adopted it. Do not be the late adopter here. The age of flexible work has arrived. Give the four day week a fair try before you decide it will not work for your business.\n\nThe biggest internal obstacle to the four day week is intellectual resistance from business leaders.\n\nEvery business is different, so the approach you use may differ from what you read about or what others have done. The point is not to be rigid. You can adjust it as much as you like, as long as the core principles hold: reduced work hours at 100 percent pay in exchange for 100 percent productivity.\n\nA flexibility or productivity policy is, at its heart, a test of leadership.\n\nWhile running your trial, do not forget to design the office as well as you can. Open offices where employees can see each other and interact freely have their advantages, but without guardrails, they can hurt productivity. Research shows that when someone working on a complex task gets distracted, it takes roughly 40 minutes to fully regain the original level of focus. You do not want that happening in your open office, so put structures in place to prevent it.\n\nOpen offices should be tied to a clear goal, such as collaboration or spontaneous lunch meetings. If there is no goal or constraint attached to the open office, leaders are usually better off letting employees work behind closed doors."
      },
      {
        title: "Closing thoughts",
        text: "During the industrial revolution in the 19th century, workers were typically on the job 60 to 70 hours per week, or 3,000 or more hours a year. These workers were mostly men, and they had little to no time for anything else outside work.\n\nWork culture was different then. You worked one job, usually for one company, your whole life. Job security existed, but work life balance was nothing to brag about, and the gender gap was wide.\n\nThat pattern held until labor got organized. People began pushing for better conditions for everyone. It was a long fight, but it led to the 40 hour workweek we now enjoy. So many Gen Z workers cannot even imagine working 60 to 70 hours a week. That is progress for humanity, and it is time to push further.\n\nThe four day week is the next stage of work. The principle can be compressed into the 100 80 100 formula, which means 100 percent pay for 80 percent of the time in return for 100 percent of the agreed productivity. The principle is employee focused and flexible in itself. When it is put in place, workers or a particular team can choose to take a full day off or to spread their hours across five shorter days. The choice is up to the workers, provided the company's bottom line is met or exceeded.\n\nThe four day week may look similar to the gig economy, but it is not. There is a clear difference between the two. The gig economy offers flexibility without the benefits that come with traditional work. The four day week is traditional work, with all its benefits, plus real flexibility. If you have to choose, pick the four day week, because your employer will offer you flexibility and will also be required by law to give you work leave, a 401K, and other benefits your region demands.\n\nTry this. Your personal productivity affects any team you join. Here is a powerful tip to lift yours. Use time blocking. Block out large chunks of time where you focus only on work, without distractions. You can also set aside a short distraction window. Call it whatever you like, but the idea is to use that window for all the side distractions that usually interrupt your work. When it is work time, you focus only on work, and when it is distraction or break time, you do whatever you want. Keep that distraction window short."
      }
    ]
  },

  "the-5-am-club.json": {
    base: { id: "the-5-am-club", title: "The 5 AM Club", author: "", type: "summary", addedAt: 1781635205936 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: "Other people can influence your output",
        text: "Section placeholder. This opening entry collects author and contributor names tied to related Headway titles. The names below appear in the original source for reference. Daniel Lieberman, MD, Michael E. Long. Lisa Damour, PhD. David Richo, Ph.D. Gabrielle Bernstein."
      },
      {
        title: "The source of true wealth and fulfillment",
        text: "Here is what the billionaire taught our two companions about real success. Every person who has left a lasting mark on history shares one trait. They stopped chasing personal gain and started serving something bigger than themselves.\n\nYou can find true wealth and fulfillment by helping and inspiring others. He also pushed back against today's social economy, which runs on the idea that people need to \"grow up\" to become successful. He believes we often forget to appreciate small things and, in contrast, grow used to the ordinary.\n\nAppearances can be deceiving. It is what lies underneath that truly matters.\n\nThe artist and the entrepreneur, drawn to the life and ideas of their new acquaintance, later met up with the billionaire to begin a mentorship that opened their eyes.\n\nFirst and foremost, their new teacher emphasized the importance of waking at 5 am and kicking off tasks that would fuel the rest of the day. He told them he had discovered his own ability to use this strategy and that it had helped him live an above average life.\n\nStarting your day in morning solitude helps you hold onto the focus you need to make the most of your daily tasks.\n\nAccording to the billionaire, generating high quality output is one of the benefits of joining the 5 am club. Drawing on his rise from mediocrity to the exceptional, he told his guests how he had learned to block every source of distraction.\n\nHe backed this up with findings from neuroscientists that our peak mental state sharpens our reasoning, which drives our perception to a new level. Combining that powerful state with a proven method, which the billionaire called the 20/20/20 formula, improves prosperity, productivity, and performance.\n\nThe formula divides the first \"Victory Hour\" of the day, from 5:00 am to 6:00 am, into three twenty minute blocks. These blocks are dedicated to \"Move\" (intense exercise), \"Reflect\" (journaling, meditation, planning), and \"Grow\" (reading, learning, reviewing goals). They aim to optimize mindset, emotions, body, and spirit for higher productivity and well being. This concept helped the billionaire sharpen his thinking and become a visionary.\n\nThat line about rising before dawn comes from Aristotle."
      },
      {
        title: "The most successful people dedicate their time to the tiniest of details",
        text: "Section placeholder. This entry lists contributor names from related Headway summaries. The names below appear in the original source for reference. Dr. Jerold J. Kreisman, MD, Hal Straus. Daniel Lieberman. Jessie Inchauspe. Lisa Mosconi, PhD. Jenara Nerenberg. Rachel Clarke, MD. Paul Kalanithi, MD. Daniel J. Siegel, MD. Daniel Lieberman, MD, Michael E. Long. Dr. Jenna Macciochi. Emily Oster, PhD. Daniel G. Amen, MD."
      },
      {
        title: "Your ability to free yourself from dead weight",
        text: "Section placeholder. This entry groups contributor names under a Sports and Fitness tag. The names below appear in the original source for reference. Tom Nichols, PhD. Patrick Radden Keefe. Elizabeth L. Cline. Carl T. Bergstrom, Jevin D. West. Jenara Nerenberg. Christian Davenport."
      },
      {
        title: "Leave your comfort zone to unlock your true potential",
        text: "Dawn breaks with an adventure that changes everything. At 5 am, the billionaire picks up his guests in a helicopter for a \"field trip.\" He later announces that they are heading back to the airport, and their next destination is Agra, India.\n\nDuring their memorable visit to the Taj Mahal, he shared another factor that separates successes from failures. He had come to understand that successful people chose to do the things the average person would find difficult. They kept repeating those hard tasks until they became habits.\n\nYour brain keeps growing if you challenge yourself to expand your horizons and leave your comfort zone.\n\nStill, the mogul pointed out that this method calls for a steady process with specific phases and no shortcuts. His approach demands constant attention, and adopters have to walk through each phase, since there are no shortcuts. Your willpower can adapt to whatever limits you set. By widening your worldview, you develop your brain even further.\n\nIt is vital to step outside your comfort zone to unlock your true potential and build the stamina that success demands. In the end, your comfort zone keeps you on the same ground you are used to. So change is necessary if you want to succeed.\n\nMany people give up halfway through their self discovery journey. The successful ones first had to shape their emotions, bodies, and spirits to match their new winning mindset. Without that flexibility, those people would not have come close to the success they reached."
      },
      {
        title: "It is not enough to wake up early",
        text: "Section placeholder. This entry gathers contributor names from related Headway summaries. The names below appear in the original source for reference. Tom Nichols, PhD. Patrick Radden Keefe. Elizabeth L. Cline. Carl T. Bergstrom, Jevin D. West. Jenara Nerenberg. Christian Davenport."
      },
      {
        title: "Sleep deprivation and oversleeping will erode your productivity",
        text: "While in the Roman catacombs, the underground tunnels where the ancient Romans buried their dead, the billionaire explained that his next lesson would touch on the essentials of sleep. It felt fitting to hold that session in a place where the occupants were in a permanent deep sleep.\n\nThis session explored the downsides of technologies that steal our sleep time. How you spend the latter part of the day matters as much as how you spend the early part. Staying up late makes it hard to wake at 5 am and put the 20/20/20 formula to work. Over time, this wears down your productivity, performance, and health.\n\nLack of sleep cuts productivity, drags down performance, lowers general happiness, and harms health.\n\nJust as sleep deprivation shrinks performance and life span, researchers have found that oversleeping is harmful to well being. Balance is the key. The Spellbinder said that seven hours of sleep is ideal. Once you get good sleep and run your morning routines, you should focus on specific tasks for the first hour and a half of work.\n\nWhen you do this, fight the urge to give in to distractions, and then find time to rest between long stretches of work. Pushing yourself too hard only drains energy and lowers productivity. Good rest keeps the creative juices flowing. You can also use that time to learn new things that broaden your horizons.\n\nMelatonin is the chemical that tells your body it is time to sleep. When you sleep, and here quality matters as much as quantity, your neurons shrink by about 60 percent as cerebrospinal fluid washes through your brain."
      },
      {
        title: "Conclusion",
        text: "Section placeholder. This closing entry lists contributor names from related Headway summaries. The names below appear in the original source for reference. Valerie Biden Owens. Patrick Radden Keefe. Eliot Brown, Maureen Farrell. Tom Satterly, Steve Jackson. Will Smith, Mark Manson. Christian Davenport. Lin-Manuel Miranda, Jeremy McCarter. Simon Sebag Montefiore, PhD. Doris Kearns Goodwin, PhD. Rachel Maddow, Michael Yarvitz. Malcolm X, Alex Haley, M. S. Handler."
      }
    ]
  }
};
